# Project Overview

Travel From Photo provides three main ways for users to explore places and routes.

1. Users can manually enter a destination name and receive a route from their current location.
2. Users can upload an image of a place they want to visit.
3. Users can upload a food photo to identify the cuisine and estimate restaurant candidates.

When a travel image is uploaded, the system first checks whether the image contains GPS metadata. If location metadata exists, the system extracts the coordinates to identify the location.

If the metadata is missing or unreliable, the system analyzes the image using computer vision techniques. If recognizable landmarks are detected, the system estimates the location based on those features.

If the image is a food photo, the system detects the food type first, then uses contextual hints such as country, city, and recent uploaded photos to narrow down likely restaurant candidates.

If the location or restaurant is still uncertain, the system allows the user to provide contextual hints such as the country or city where the photo was taken. These hints help narrow down candidate locations using a place search API.

After the destination is identified, the system generates the shortest travel route from the user's current location to the destination and displays it on the web interface.

---

# System Architecture

```text
User
|
| Upload Travel Photo / Food Photo / Enter Destination
v
Frontend (Web Application)
|
| HTTP Request
v
Backend Server (FastAPI)
|
|-- EXIF Metadata Extraction
|-- Computer Vision Analysis
|   |-- Landmark Detection
|   `-- Image Embedding / Similarity Search
|-- Food Recognition
|   |-- Cuisine Detection
|   `-- Restaurant Candidate Matching
|-- User Hint Processing
|   |-- Country / City Input
|   `-- Recent Uploaded Photo Context
|-- Places API
|   `-- Candidate Location / Restaurant Search
`-- Directions API
    `-- Route Generation
|
v
Frontend Map Visualization
```

# Workflow

1. The user uploads a travel photo, uploads a food photo, or enters a destination manually.
2. The backend checks whether the image contains GPS metadata.
3. If GPS metadata exists, the system uses it to determine the location.
4. If GPS metadata is not available, the system analyzes the image using computer vision.
5. If landmarks are detected, the system estimates the place from visual features.
6. If the image is food, the system identifies the cuisine or meal type.
7. The user may provide contextual hints such as country or city.
8. Recently uploaded photos can be reused as extra context for restaurant estimation.
9. The system searches candidate locations or restaurants using a place search API.
10. Once the destination is identified, the system generates the shortest route.
11. The route is displayed on the map in the web interface.

